segments.text: We're concerned with the production of the final product and its marketing.
This has been a rather successful strategy because we're working with the producers and with the large volume processors who see us as friends and we're not competing with
the grocery products companies who would otherwise see us as their competitors if we were developing final products for the marketplace.
More recently, we have taken a look at our program and decided that we really were in the extraction or separation processes business, although we currently have about $1 million
a year research budget, and most of it is spent on oilseed processing.
We recognize that the techniques that we use are applicable to processing of other crops, other non-edible crops.
Early this spring, we established a new section in the Food Protein Research and Development Center.
It's called the Separation Processes Laboratory.
The objective there is to concentrate on the science and engineering of separation and to also work on other applications such as industrial crops.
Within the last five years, there's been increasing interest in the replenishable resources.
This means the growing of crops to replace fossil energy and hydrocarbon sources.
In other words, growing of our own liquid fuels, lubricating oils.
her own chemical feedstocks rather than relying on drilled petroleum or mined coal.
We feel that this work will continue, although there certainly will be a strong petroleum industry and perhaps even a stronger coal industry in the future.
And thus we have ventured into the separation processes area and
have done and are doing some work with agricultural crops that are non-edible.
We have worked with jojoba, J-O-J-O-B-A, which is an arid lands crop.
It produces a oil.
Well, it's a perennial bush that has
seeds or nuts, which when crushed produce an oil that is very similar to whale oil.
Rather than being composed of triglycerides, it's composed of aliphatic esters.
That means you have straight chain rather than branch type of fat in jojoba oil.

As such, it is a highly stable oil and is used in high pressure lubrication applications such as jet aircraft, automatic transmissions, permanent lubricated type of motors, equipment, things of this nature.
We're also currently working
on extraction of latex or rubber from Guayule, that's spelled G-U-A-Y-U-L-E.
This is another shrub that grows along the U.S.-Mexico border in the arid lands region from, say, the Big Bend
west through to California.
The shrub contains a latex which, when extracted, is very similar to natural rubber from Havilla.
That's H-A-V-E-A.
or the rubber tree that is cultivated in the Dutch East Indies and in Central Africa.
Many people don't realize that after petroleum, our next largest import in terms of dollars is rubber in the United States.
And we can no longer, as a nation,
rely on the rubber producing areas staying within the free world group of countries.
Certainly our experiences in Vietnam have shown this as well as the various revolutions and coups in Africa.
In case of a war or even a
period of political hardening, the United States would be in a very vulnerable position if it lost its supply of rubber and could no longer import it.
Synthetic rubber is very important to our economy, but it will not replace natural rubber.
Fairly large amounts
of natural rubber are required for high performance applications such as military aircraft, tires, engine mounts, tank treads, and this type of application.
Also, as the U.S. has gone from larger to smaller cars and to radial tires, the average
natural rubber content to the tire has had to increase because of the higher performance requirements.
Synthetic rubber just will not substitute completely for natural rubber, and there is need for developing a better solution to our national rubber needs.
We are working on developing processes for extracting this latex from the Wai'uli bush.
Unlike the avia, a rubber tree which grows large and can be slashed and then the rubber or latex bled into a container, the Wai'uli bush at
say three to five years, which would be normal harvest time, would be only two and a half to four feet tall.
And there's no way to slash and bleed them.
You really have got to either polarize them, that means cut the top branches off, or else dig up the whole plant, and then it has to be
ground, shredded to release the latex through one of several processes.
We feel that there's going to be additional industrial products interest in the country as time goes by.
And this is why we have established a separation processes laboratory.

Getting back to the oilseeds processing area, in recent years we have taken the position that our main role is to improve the profitability of oilseeds production and processing for the Texas farmer and processor and the U.S. producer and processor.
As such, we have broadened our base to include various concerns such as energy conservation, dust control, development of usable
and really available solvents, improving extraction efficiency, and also improving the feed value of the byproducts.
For a while, the emphasis at the center, this was during the 70s, was on developing low-cost, developing sources and processes for low-cost food proteins

However, we have found that the U.S. being an exporter of food products is far from being on a vegetable protein economy, and even the developing countries aren't quite ready to use some of these vegetable proteins that have been developed.
So the emphasis has intentionally shifted to improve the productivity and profitability of the local processing industry.
What are some of the methods that your research program is funded by?
You mentioned that you had a budget of about a million dollars a year.
We receive about 12% to 15% of our funding through the engineering experiment station.
This is primarily to be used as seed money, program development money, holdover money, say, when our people are working between various projects.
About 40% of our funding comes through the Natural Fibers and Food Coordination Commission of Texas.
It's a group that is separately funded by the
state legislature and its objective is to develop new uses and expand the uses of Texas grown crops as well as assist in the development of the processing industry for them.
We then have about 20% of our funding from
federal competitive type of grants and the balance about 25% from industry programs.
We have two industry programs.
One is the contract research program where we do contract research for firms.
The other is a industry services program where we make our pilot plant available to, our pilot plant equipment and train operators available to
companies who want to come in and try various combinations of equipment for developing new processes.
As I see it, the area that is most likely to grow will be that of the industry services and the industry research programs.
I expect that the state
Originated funds will probably grow with inflation, which really means no actual increase.
And the federal programs will probably be held rather in tight reign by the current and subsequent administrations.
So really our future,
It depends on our ability to recruit research work directly from industry.
We've been fairly successful in doing this.
What are some of the industries that have hired your researchers to do projects for them?
We've had various groups come in.
want to try our extraction equipment, for example, on various items, including spices, nuts, rather unusual items.
We have had a program recently from Shell Oil Company, who would like to develop a market for a new type of solvent to replace hexane.
They're working in isopropyl alcohol, and they're working in conjunction with Anderson Clayton Company, who is probably the single largest processor of cottonseed in the country.
They also have soybean interests.
We have developed various procedures for utilizing isopropanol.
We also have done contract research for to improve the recovery of oil.
Our program is of an international type.
Well, let's say a national and international type.
Originally, when the oil varieties of sunflower were brought back to the United States from Russia,
You have to remember that sunflower is an American crop first, but it's a short-season crop.
Where does it grow mainly?
Well, currently the cultivated varieties grow mainly in the tri-state area of North and South Dakota and Minnesota.
Originally it was a wild plant that grew in the Midwestern states.
The plant is a short-season crop and very attractive to countries that have short growing seasons.
This is why the Russians picked it up in the late 1800s, and they put quite a bit of effort into improving its genetics and productivity.
In time, they developed varieties that were very high in oil content.
What they did was they were able to decrease the thickness of the hull.
Therefore, the head would have more seed and produce more oil per acre.
When these varieties were brought back to the US in the early 1960s, the work on their growing and processing was initially done here at Texas A&M.
Much of the processing work in this department, not exclusively,
We have still continued to have an interest in sunflower processing and are probably the most, well, we are the most active U.S. group, even though the industry has gone north.
Over the years, it's become apparent that cotton is much more profitable in Texas than sunflower.
However, the northern states have found that sunflower is more profitable than their alternative crops,
wheat, and barley and oats.

Recently the U.S. has, recently plants, oil seed processing plants, sunflower plants have been built in the northern states, but the engineering companies in getting the processing information, particularly the hulling information on seed hulling,
have used our facilities to check out the applicability of cotton seed haulers.
We are currently doing some work on cotton seed processing for an engineering company that operates out of Paris, France.
Black Nations of Africa, which were under French control as colonies, later re-invited the French back to work with them in developing their businesses.
This particular company is very active in cocoa and coffee.
trading, export, and also processing, and has asked us to work with him on extraction of various fractions from these crops.
Another area that we are getting into that I might mention, it's a good example of how when you look upon your business as being
function rather than commodity oriented, you immediately recognize other applications.
We currently are applying reverse osmosis membranes to processing of stripped beer from alcohol fermentation.
There's been quite an active program here at A&M
developing gasohol production techniques.
Agriculture engineering has led the program.
They have a small alcohol fermentation plant in the shops next door.
Eventually, they mix the alcohol, about 10% alcohol, with gas things to produce gasohol.
But when one
ferments sorghum or corn into alcohol, it's necessary to run this process at rather dilute concentrations.
The beer, which is the fermented liquid, at the end of the process is run through distillation columns, and the alcohol is distilled off.
However, the remaining beer,
or spent worth, as you call it, presents certain problems.
First of all, it's too dilute for animal feeding.
Some of it can be consumed by animals, but you really would bloat the cows pretty badly if you expected them to get all the nutrition from it.
And, of course, it presents disposal problems.
If one were to dehydrate it, for example, or dry it, the energy required would far exceed that gained by producing alcohol.
So we are using reverse osmosis as a means of recovering the water and concentrating the soluble so that they can be used as feed.
And there are many other applications
we can point to.
As far as the future is concerned, I think that we'll be working more broadly with other agricultural crops and also with extraction processes per se.
The extraction processes including milling, separation, cleaning,
have neglected for a very long time.
And in many cases, we are limited in our food and industrial applications by the purity of the materials we have.
We feel that we can make quite a contribution in developing more usable ingredients from agricultural crops.
Do you think there's any certain food that would be the food of the future as far as protein?
Not one certain food, but I think that we're going to have to be more efficient, more economic, so to speak, about using the available calories and proteins.
Really, that's all that.
that we have to work with.
As the world's population density increases, we're going to have to use every technique possible to raise enough food.
This, in some cases, means expanding the grazing lands in some countries because
When you have a very sparse vegetation, cows, and especially the smaller animals like sheep and goats, can still harvest some type of food from the land.
They can harvest and concentrate it, so the man then can, of course, use the meat.
I think there's going to be a general,
trend towards more use of vegetable food proteins directly rather than by recycling them through animals.
By no means do I mean that we're going to do without animals, because when you process oilseeds or cereals directly into human food products, you
very often have as much as 50% byproducts.
And the only way to get the nutrients out of these materials is by recycling them through animals.
Animals really are sort of a very useful biological machine.
They will concentrate the protein as well as the available calories more efficiently than some of the machines that
that we know how to build.
Of course, when you have a prime grain or an oil seed, say like a soybean or wheat, animals are relatively inefficient in that their conversion rate is relatively low.
It takes about four or five pounds
protein to put a powder protein on an animal, for example.
But where your only choice is residues from processing or grazing land, I think animals are very efficient and they'll stay.
We'll probably be seeing even more ruminants
as time goes by, and probably less of those animals that compete directly with man, such as swine and poultry.
Of course, it depends upon where you are.
Here in the United States, we will, I'm sure, stay on an animal protein economy for many years.
Other countries,
have enough problems feeding themselves right now, including getting enough money to import our crops just to stay alive on a vegetable protein diet.
Do you have any figures on what percent of the people in this country are not getting enough protein in their diet?
Not just off the top of my head.
Actually, protein is relatively inexpensive.
I think that where people are not getting enough protein or calories, it's a matter of education and appreciation.
We are not protein deficient as a nation.
Are some nations protein deficient?
The countries that have high...

birth rates and where say the where advances are being made in medical science and people continue to live and continue to live on for a long time they are squeezed from both ends yes yes I'd say that you can almost draw
draw a band around the world, around the equator, and you'll find many of the countries there being protein deficient.
That is because there just isn't enough protein to raise, to go around for the people.
Actually, there is more than enough protein in the world.
Many of the problems are those of concentrating it
away from, say, the fiber.
And then, of course, we have the problem of distribution and the economics that go along with it.
In the United States, for example, we raise enough protein to feed about 1.5 to 2 billion people.
Of course, we're a relatively small country.
I don't know what we have.
230 million.
230 million, but I think only 12% or 15% of the world's land mass.
Maybe not even that much.
Less than that.
Less than that, maybe 8%.
So if we can grow that much protein, certainly protein is not scarce.
The problem is one of getting the protein to people.
As I was alluding to earlier,
When it comes to nutrition, there are only two basic things that man must rely on the environment for.
One is the calories.
He can't make them because he needs the calories for his energy.
The other is certain amino acids.
And these are, they're limited to amino acids, and only plants can make some of them.
And whether man eats the plants directly or whether he eats an animal, eats the plants, we come into a cycle where only these essential amino acids can be produced by plants.
And the question is how to get it to man, whether you get it to him directly or
or recycle it and concentrate it, say, through animals.
Is there anything you'd like to say in closing?
No, I think that I'm pretty optimistic as far as both the center and food science is concerned.
I think the golden years are ahead of us really in terms of contributions that we'll be able to make both to the state of Texas and to the
to the world.
We're starting this fall a series of practical short courses in oil mill operations.
It's our first venture into the technical training area.
There seems to be quite a built up demand and many industry leaders have encouraged us to go into this field.
I think we can serve a very useful purpose both in Texas and the U.S. and in the world.
Thank you very much for talking with me tonight, Dr. Lewis.
